<HEADLINE>
<P>
GERRY ADAMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Re "N. Ireland: Time for Real Debate," editorial, Oct. 7: 
</P>
<P>
 I loved the Gilbertian humor of your editorial, in which you call upon the 
British to allow Gerry Adams (president of the Irish nationalist party Sinn 
Fein) to visit London -- the capital of the United Kingdom. The British claim 
that, as one prime minister put it, "Northern Ireland is as much a part of the 
United Kingdom as Yorkshire."Under British law, Adams is a citizen of the 
United Kingdom. At one time, he was an elected member of the United Kingdom 
Parliament. Yet he is banned from visiting London. A rough analogy in this 
country would be to restrict Sen. Edward Kennedy to Massachusetts and deny him 
entry to any of the other 49 states. 
</P>
<P>
 On reflection, that is not such a bad idea. 
</P>
<P>
 JOSEPH McEVOY 
</P>
<P>
 Huntington Beach 
</P>
