<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY ALMANAC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It's taken 23 years of debate, lawsuits and destruction, but downtown Brea is 
finally showing signs of new life. 
</P>
<P>
 The historic downtown strip along Brea Boulevard is the site of a 
controversial redevelopment effort that resulted in the bulldozing of several 
landmarks, including the Red Lantern Theater, where Judy Garland once 
performed. 
</P>
<P>
 Gateway Center, the first phase of the redevelopment project, is expected the 
open later this fall. The 22-acre shopping complex consists of a supermarket, 
restaurants and specialty shops. By 1996, officials hope to add a pedestrian 
mall featuring movie theaters, fountains and public art. 
</P>
<P>
 Today 
</P>
<P>
 The Newport Beach Central Library will host an orientation to familiarize 
patrons with the library's business information resources. 
</P>
<P>
 The free program, which begins at 7:30 a.m., will acquaint participants with 
both printed and computerized information sources as well as tools in the 
library's new business section. 
</P>
<P>
 The library is at 1000 Avocado Ave., a block north of Coast Highway and a 
block west of MacArthur Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
 Information: (714) 717-3801. 
</P>
