<HEADLINE>
<P>
THREATT'S ABSENCE LEAVES ANGRY LAKERS IN THE DARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Lakers late Sunday night were still awaiting an explanation for Sedale 
Threatt's sudden unexcused departure from training camp in Honolulu early 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm not looking for him," said an obviously angry executive vice president 
Jerry West, who returned to Los Angeles on Sunday night after the end of the 
team's camp in Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
 "We'd like to know what is going on because we have no clue. . . . But, 
obviously, we have tried to run him down and have gotten no return calls back 
so we assume it is something he will have to work out. He knows the 
consequences. 
</P>
<P>
 "He will be fined. Period. If he had a problem we would have helped him try to 
resolve the problem." 
</P>
<P>
 Threatt will earn $2.4 million each of the next two seasons, considerable 
salary for a reserve guard. Threatt is expected to be a key member of the team, 
primarily as a back up to starting point guard Nick Van Exel. 
</P>
<P>
 Threatt, an 11-year NBA veteran, apparently flew back to the mainland before 
the team's second exhibition, a 125-120 victory over the Sacramento Kings on 
Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
 Before his absence, Threatt slid a note under West's door at the team's 
Honolulu hotel asking to speak with him, but did not call West. 
</P>
<P>
 West said he spoke with agent Jim Sexton, but said Sexton had not talked to 
Threatt. 
</P>
<P>
 Sexton could not be reached for comment on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 In Friday's preseason opener, Threatt played 17 minutes and scored six points, 
all on free throws. 
</P>
<P>
 Threatt was drafted by Philadelphia in the sixth round in 1983. He also played 
for Chicago and Seattle before being traded to the Lakers in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101794-0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 089540 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
October 17, 1994, Monday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
